PROPOSED ORDER GRANTING EMERGENCY MOTION TO RESTORE PARENTING TIME


At a session of said Court held at the
Muskegon County Hall of Justice
in the City of Muskegon, County of Muskegon,
State of Michigan, on ________________, 2026


PRESENT: HON. JENNY L. McNEILL
          Circuit Court Judge


This matter came before the Court on Plaintiff Andrew J. Pigors' Emergency Motion to Restore Parenting Time. The Court, having reviewed the motion, supporting brief, affidavit, and all materials on file, and being fully advised in the premises, finds as follows:

FINDINGS OF FACT

1. Lincoln Watson Pigors (DOB: June 27, 2018) is the minor child of the parties.

2. Plaintiff's parenting time has been suspended since August 8, 2025, a period of ONE HUNDRED NINETY-TWO (192) consecutive days as of February 11, 2026.

3. The August 8, 2025 ex parte order suspending parenting time was entered without a verified pleading or affidavit as required by MCR 3.207(B).

4. The August 8, 2025 order contains no written findings that immediate and irreparable harm would result before the matter could be heard on notice, as required by MCR 3.207(B).

5. No clear and convincing evidence has been presented demonstrating that Plaintiff's parenting time would endanger Lincoln's physical, mental, or emotional health as required by MCL 722.27a(3).

6. The Court has not made the specific written findings required by MCL 722.27a(3) and MCR 3.210(D) to support denial or restriction of parenting time.

7. A comprehensive mental health evaluation conducted by HealthWest at the Court's direction found no basis to restrict Plaintiff's parenting time and recommended substantial parenting time.

8. Medical records contain no evidence of harm to Lincoln during Plaintiff's parenting time.

9. Police reports contain no substantiated allegations of danger, abuse, or neglect by Plaintiff.

10. Lincoln is six (6) years old, a critical developmental age during which prolonged separation from a parent causes documented psychological harm including attachment disruption, abandonment trauma, and relationship difficulties.

11. Each additional day of separation causes ongoing, immediate, and irreparable harm to Lincoln and to the father-child relationship.

12. This is the third instance of Defendant withholding or suspending Plaintiff's parenting time, for a total of 329 days of wrongful deprivation.

CONCLUSIONS OF LAW

13. The August 8, 2025 ex parte order suspending Plaintiff's parenting time is VOID for failure to comply with MCR 3.207(B), which requires ex parte relief to be supported by "specific facts shown by affidavit or by a verified pleading" demonstrating "immediate and irreparable injury, loss, or damage will result to the moving party before the adverse party or the adverse party's attorney can be heard in opposition."

14. Michigan Court Rules must be strictly complied with, and substantial compliance is insufficient. Grievance Administrator v. Fieger, 476 Mich 231, 244 (2006).

15. MCL 722.27a establishes a statutory presumption that parenting time "will not endanger the child's physical, mental, or emotional health" and requires "clear and convincing evidence" to overcome this presumption.

16. The record contains no clear and convincing evidence that Plaintiff's parenting time would endanger Lincoln.

17. The suspension of Plaintiff's parenting time without proper notice, hearing, or findings violates Plaintiff's Fourteenth Amendment due process rights in the parent-child relationship, a fundamental liberty interest. Troxel v. Granville, 530 US 57 (2000); Stanley v. Illinois, 405 US 645 (1972).

18. The 192-day separation causes irreparable harm to Lincoln and to the father-child relationship that cannot be adequately remedied after-the-fact. Pontiac Fire Fighters Union Local 376 v. City of Pontiac, 482 Mich 1, 9 (2008).

19. Immediate restoration of parenting time is necessary to prevent further irreparable harm and to protect Plaintiff's constitutional rights and Lincoln's best interests.

20. Defendant's pattern of gatekeeping and withholding parenting time violates Michigan's statutory framework protecting parenting time and harms Lincoln. MCL 722.23(c); MCL 722.27a(8).

ORDER

IT IS HEREBY ORDERED:

1. VACATED ORDER: The August 8, 2025 ex parte order suspending Plaintiff Andrew J. Pigors' parenting time is VACATED effective immediately.

2. RESTORATION OF PARENTING TIME: Plaintiff's parenting time is RESTORED to the schedule established in the July 17, 2024 custody order, providing Plaintiff 79 overnights per year, effective immediately as follows:

   SCHEDULE:
   • Every other weekend from Friday at 6:00 PM to Sunday at 6:00 PM
   • One midweek overnight per week from Wednesday at 6:00 PM to Thursday at 8:00 AM
   • [Additional schedule details as established in July 17, 2024 order]

3. IMMEDIATE EXCHANGE: Defendant Emily A. Watson SHALL make Lincoln available to Plaintiff for parenting time beginning THIS WEEKEND, [DATE], at 6:00 PM at [EXCHANGE LOCATION].

4. FACILITATION REQUIRED: Defendant SHALL facilitate the immediate resumption of Plaintiff's parenting time without interference, obstruction, delay, or negative messaging to Lincoln regarding Plaintiff or the resumption of parenting time.

5. PROHIBITED CONDUCT: Defendant is PROHIBITED from:
   a. Unilaterally withholding, suspending, or denying Plaintiff's parenting time;
   b. Making negative statements to Lincoln about Plaintiff;
   c. Interfering with Plaintiff's communication with Lincoln;
   d. Questioning Lincoln about his time with Plaintiff in a manner designed to elicit negative responses;
   e. Presenting Lincoln with a choice about whether to participate in parenting time;
   f. Otherwise engaging in parental alienation or gatekeeping behaviors.

6. MAKEUP PARENTING TIME: Within seven (7) days of this order, the parties SHALL meet (in person, by phone, or through counsel) to propose a makeup parenting time schedule to compensate Plaintiff for the 192+ days of wrongfully withheld parenting time. If the parties cannot agree, either party may file a motion for the Court to establish a makeup schedule.

7. EVIDENTIARY HEARING SCHEDULED: An evidentiary hearing is SCHEDULED for [DATE] at [TIME] to address:
   a. An appropriate makeup parenting time schedule;
   b. Whether modification of custody is warranted based on Defendant's pattern of gatekeeping;
   c. Whether sanctions are appropriate against Defendant for parental alienation and violation of parenting time orders;
   d. Whether therapeutic support for Lincoln is necessary to facilitate reunification;
   e. Any other matters relevant to Lincoln's best interests and enforcement of parenting time.

8. THERAPEUTIC SUPPORT: The parties MAY agree to engage a therapist to assist Lincoln with the transition and reunification with Plaintiff. If the parties agree on a therapist, the cost shall be shared equally. If therapeutic support becomes necessary as determined at the evidentiary hearing, the Court will enter appropriate orders.

9. COMMUNICATION: The parties SHALL communicate regarding Lincoln's needs, schedules, and parenting time logistics using [co-parenting app or other method established in prior order]. All communication shall be respectful, child-focused, and free from disparagement.

10. COMPLIANCE REQUIRED: Both parties SHALL comply with all terms of this order. Violation of this order may result in sanctions including but not limited to:
    a. Modification of custody;
    b. Makeup parenting time;
    c. Monetary sanctions;
    d. Attorney fees;
    e. Contempt proceedings;
    f. Referral to law enforcement or child protective services if appropriate.

11. PROHIBITION ON FUTURE EX PARTE RELIEF: Any future motion to suspend, modify, or restrict Plaintiff's parenting time MUST:
    a. Be filed as a noticed motion with adequate notice to Plaintiff;
    b. Be supported by a verified pleading or affidavit with specific facts;
    c. Include a proposed order with specific findings;
    d. Demonstrate clear and convincing evidence of endangerment as required by MCL 722.27a(3);
    e. Comply strictly with MCR 3.207(B) if ex parte relief is sought.

12. CONSTITUTIONAL PROTECTIONS REAFFIRMED: The Court reaffirms that Plaintiff's relationship with Lincoln is a fundamental constitutional right protected by the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment, and that deprivation of this right requires strict procedural protections and clear and convincing evidence of necessity.

13. STATUTORY PRESUMPTION REAFFIRMED: The Court reaffirms the statutory presumption established by MCL 722.27a that parenting time with Plaintiff will not endanger Lincoln and that this presumption can only be overcome by clear and convincing evidence.

14. RETENTION OF JURISDICTION: The Court retains jurisdiction to enforce this order and to enter further orders as necessary to protect Lincoln's best interests and the parties' rights.

15. EFFECTIVE DATE: This order is effective immediately upon signing and shall remain in effect until modified by further order of this Court.

IT IS SO ORDERED.


